\begin_layout Section
Python, Sage and SageCell
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Historically, we used the numerical computing environment and programming
 language Matlab to teach numerical methods in mechanical engineering, because
 of its ease of use for beginners and the large amount of available toolboxes.
 However, Matlab is not a real programming language and students tended
 to learn only how to write Matlab script using black-box libraries functions
 instead of basic scientific algorithm.
 But in recent years, we use 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Scientific Python
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 to teach scientific computing, because Python, by definition, is a programming
 language.
 Indeed Python is a beautiful programming language, with great readibility
 that makes it a good choice as a first programming language.
 With the scientific librairies (Nympy, Scipy and Matplotlib), it is a better
 alternative to Matlab to teach numerical methods in mechanical engineering.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To allow our students to use Python without installing the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Scientific Python stack
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 on their computer, we use a Sage web-server (
\begin_inset Flex URL
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

http://sage-meca.univ-lyon1.fr
\end_layout

\end_inset

), based on the free open-source mathematics software Sage 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "sage"

\end_inset

.
 We also use a Sage Cell Server, which is an open-source, scalable, and
 easy-to-use web interface to Sage, that allow to embed Sage computations
 into any web-page.
 The Sage cell server in the MOOC InPros will be used as an interactive
 activity while watching the video of the course, to allow the student to
 redo the examples described in the course (see Figure 
